        <p> ___Twig_token_1___ There would have been a thunderstorm. I missed it completely. It remains to be seen whether this is due to the fresh mountain air or my inner calm - at least I woke up well in the morning. </p>
        <p> It was rather fresh in the car - we call it "Alpine's indoor climate". So: heating on. But as soon as the good piece ran, it was already pounding vigorously on the door. Our camping neighbor interpreted with a concerned look at the white cloud of smoke that enveloped our car. Ups! No fire alarm - just a kind of involuntary pope election. White smoke rose and we already thought: "Have you just opened a new council?" </p>
        <p> So quickly go out with the heating, take a deep breath and first wake up really. Then we ventured a second attempt under strict observation. The internet, our digital camping consultant, recommended that heat through for an hour, then the spook should be over. And lo and behold - after five minutes the white fog was history. There was probably just too much moisture in the system. Or someone had lit a incense stick in the exhaust. </p>
        <p> Around 11 a.m. it finally stopped raining - at least long enough that you didn't have to go back to the rain jacket. So in the hiking shoes and off. The bus went to the end of the Kleinwalsertal, to Baad - a small, quiet place that scores with a lot of mountain idyll. </p>

